File: platform/mcp-server/src/mcp-setup.ts. The tools/list handler is inside `registerMcpHandlers` (line 180). Extract the body into:

```typescript
export const getEnabledToolsList = (state: ServerState): Array<{ name: string; description: string; inputSchema: Record<string, unknown> }> => {
  const tools = [];
  for (const plugin of state.plugins.values()) {
    for (const toolDef of plugin.tools) {
      const prefixed = prefixedToolName(plugin.name, toolDef.name);
      if (!isToolEnabled(state, prefixed)) continue;
      tools.push({ name: prefixed, description: trustTierPrefix(plugin.trustTier) + toolDef.description, inputSchema: toolDef.input_schema });
    }
  }
  for (const cached of state.cachedBrowserTools) {
    tools.push({ name: cached.name, description: cached.description, inputSchema: cached.inputSchema });
  }
  return tools;
};
```

Then the handler becomes: `server.setRequestHandler(ListToolsRequestSchema, () => ({ tools: getEnabledToolsList(state) }));`

Add tests in mcp-setup.test.ts. Use `createState()`, set up plugins with `state.plugins.set(...)`, set `state.toolConfig`, call `rebuildToolLookups(state)` to populate `cachedBrowserTools`, then call `getEnabledToolsList(state)` and assert on the returned array. Look at existing tests in that file for the pattern. Import `getEnabledToolsList` from `./mcp-setup.js`. For browser tools in tests, add entries to `state.browserTools` before calling `rebuildToolLookups()`.

